Title:
Amsi-Bypass-Powershell

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository is a collection of PowerShell-based AMSI (Antimalware Scan Interface) bypass/avoidance techniques aggregated from public research and blog posts.  
- It targets the common problem of PowerShell payloads being scanned and blocked at runtime by AMSI-integrated AV/EDR engines.  
- Techniques include in-memory patching of AMSI-related functions (e.g., `AmsiScanBuffer`, `AmsiOpenSession`), CLR/.NET method pointer manipulation and hooking, provider-level interception/patching (e.g., `MpOav.dll`), ScriptBlock AST manipulation (“ScriptBlock Smuggling”), and logging bypasses.  
- The README notes many snippets are signature-detected and suggests modifying triggers via renaming/encoding/obfuscation and using tools like AMSITrigger/Invoke-Obfuscation to regain execution.  
- Useful primarily for red teams, pentesters, and offensive security researchers studying AMSI internals and bypass tradecraft; secondarily for defenders to understand common bypass primitives and detection opportunities.  
- Interesting because it consolidates multiple bypass classes (patching, hooking, AST tricks, provider tampering) and references original sources for deeper technical context.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI internals and patch points (`AmsiScanBuffer`, `AmsiOpenSession`, `AmsiUtils.ScanContent`)
- In-memory patching via `VirtualProtect`/`WriteProcessMemory` and shellcode stubs
- .NET/CLR method hooking and reflection-based pointer swapping
- ScriptBlock AST manipulation / ScriptBlock Smuggling
- AMSI provider interception and patching (e.g., `MpOav.dll`, provider vtables)
- PowerShell logging bypasses (ScriptBlock logging, WMF autologging)

Use Cases:
- Evaluate AMSI resilience and bypass detection in controlled red team engagements
- Research and compare multiple AMSI bypass primitives and their prerequisites (x86/x64, PS versions)
- Build defensive detections for memory patching, AMSI tampering, and suspicious reflection/AST behavior
- Reproduce and validate public AMSI bypass research techniques for training/lab environments

Keywords:
AMSI, Antimalware Scan Interface, PowerShell, AmsiScanBuffer, AmsiOpenSession, System.Management.Automation, AmsiUtils, ScanContent, VirtualProtect, WriteProcessMemory, ReadProcessMemory, CLR hooking, reflection, RuntimeHelpers.PrepareMethod, ScriptBlock, AST, ScriptBlock Smuggling, MpOav.dll, provider interception, ScriptBlockLogging, WMF5 autologging